## UI Design & Feature Planning

When designing interfaces or planning features, **always prioritize reusing the existing building blocks published at https://ui.angular-material.dev/** before considering custom implementations. These blocks provide production-ready, accessible, Material Design 3-aligned UI modules that align with this project's stack.

### Workflow

1. **Discover**: Before proposing a new component or layout, browse the block catalog at https://ui.angular-material.dev/ to identify an existing block that satisfies the requirement (e.g., authentication, dashboards, data tables, forms, navigation, marketing sections).
2. **Interact via MCP**: Use the **`ngm-dev-blocks` MCP server** (Angular Material Block) for all block-related interactions. Do **not** copy-paste code from the website manually — drive the workflow through the MCP tools so that the generated code, styles, and dependencies stay consistent with the catalog's source of truth.
3. **Integrate**: Compose the returned block into the target feature, then adjust only what is necessary for the domain logic. Preserve the block's accessibility semantics, Material theming tokens, and change detection strategy.
4. **Fallback**: Only build a bespoke component when no existing block covers the requirement, or when the existing block cannot be adapted without compromising maintainability. Document the reason in the component's header comment.

### MCP Tools (`ngm-dev-blocks`)

The following tools are exposed by the `ngm-dev-blocks` MCP server configured in `.mcp.json`:

| Tool | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `get-all-block-names` | List every available block name in the catalog. Use this first to scan the options. |
| `generate-angular-material-block` | Retrieve the full source for a specific block (TS / HTML / CSS and dependencies) by name. |
| `setup-angular-material-blocks` | Initialize the project with the shared dependencies and configuration required by the block library. Run once per project. |

### Rules

- **Discovery first**: Invoke `get-all-block-names` before designing a screen, so the proposal is grounded in what the catalog actually offers.
- **MCP-driven code**: Never hand-write a block that exists in the catalog. Always pull it through `generate-angular-material-block` so upgrades stay traceable.
- **One-time setup**: If the project has not yet been initialized for Angular Material Blocks, run `setup-angular-material-blocks` before generating individual blocks.
- **Stack alignment**: Blocks returned by the MCP server already follow this document's Angular v20+ conventions (standalone, signals, OnPush, native control flow). Preserve these conventions when integrating.
- **Accessibility preserved**: Do not strip ARIA attributes, focus management, or semantic elements from generated blocks during integration.

## Angular Project Management via Angular CLI MCP

When performing Angular project management, architectural discovery, pattern lookup, or best-practice verification, **always drive the workflow through the `angular-cli` MCP server** (configured in `.mcp.json` as `npx -y @angular/cli mcp`). Do **not** rely solely on training data for Angular APIs — the framework evolves rapidly, and the MCP server is the canonical bridge to the current Angular documentation, CLI workspace, and curated examples.

### When to Use

| Scenario | Action |
|---|---|
| Need to understand the workspace layout (apps, libs, projects) | Call `list_projects` |
| Need current best practices for a feature (signals, forms, routing, SSR, etc.) | Call `get_best_practices` |
| Need a concrete code sample for a modern Angular API | Call `find_examples` |
| Need authoritative documentation for any Angular concept or API | Call `search_documentation` |
| Need interactive, step-by-step learning on an unfamiliar feature | Call `ai_tutor` |

### MCP Tools (`angular-cli`)

Default tools (always available):

| Tool | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `list_projects` | Reads `angular.json` to enumerate all applications and libraries in the workspace. Use **before** generating code or scaffolding, so the target project is explicit. |
| `get_best_practices` | Returns contemporary Angular standards (standalone components, typed forms, signals, control flow, etc.). Use **before** proposing architecture, and again **during** code review to verify alignment. |
| `find_examples` | Retrieves curated code samples for modern, new, or recently updated Angular features. Use when you need a concrete reference implementation rather than prose. |
| `search_documentation` | Queries the official documentation at angular.dev. Use whenever an Angular API, decorator, or concept is referenced — do not guess from memory. |
| `ai_tutor` | Launches an interactive AI-powered Angular tutor. Use for deeper, conversational exploration of a feature (e.g., when onboarding an unfamiliar subsystem). |

Experimental tools (opt-in via `--experimental-tool`, not enabled by default):

- `build` — execute `ng build` for one-off compilation
- `devserver.start` / `devserver.stop` / `devserver.wait_for_build` — manage a watched dev server
- `e2e` — run end-to-end tests
- `test` — execute unit tests
- `modernize` — perform code migrations aligned with the latest Angular practices

> Experimental tools modify the workspace or execute long-running processes. Do **not** enable or invoke them without explicit user approval — follow the Automation Governance rule in the user-level CLAUDE.md (human approval required for environment changes, file modifications, destructive operations).

### Workflow

1. **Discover the workspace**: Call `list_projects` at the start of any non-trivial task so the target project, its type (application vs. library), and its configuration are explicit.
2. **Anchor on current best practices**: Before designing or refactoring, call `get_best_practices` for the relevant topic (e.g., "reactive forms", "signals", "SSR hydration"). Let the authoritative guidance override assumptions from training data.
3. **Ground code in real examples**: When an unfamiliar pattern is needed, call `find_examples` first; use the returned sample as the skeleton, then adapt.
4. **Verify API details on demand**: Whenever referencing an Angular API, directive, decorator, or CLI flag, call `search_documentation` to confirm the signature and semantics match the current Angular version.
5. **Combine with UI workflow**: For UI tasks, the block-catalog workflow via `ngm-dev-blocks` takes precedence for component markup, while `angular-cli` handles framework-level concerns (routing, DI, SSR, forms, testing, workspace). Use them together.

### Rules

- **MCP-first discovery**: Never describe Angular architecture, APIs, or best practices from memory when an MCP call can confirm them. Training data may be outdated; the MCP server is the source of truth.
- **Workspace-aware**: Always run `list_projects` before generating code in a multi-project workspace, so the correct `project` target is used.
- **Read-only by default**: Treat the `angular-cli` MCP server as read-only for project management. Invoking experimental tools that mutate the workspace or start background processes requires explicit user approval.
- **Cite the source**: When a recommendation comes from `search_documentation` or `get_best_practices`, mention it so the user can trace the rationale.
- **No blind guessing**: If `search_documentation` contradicts a memorized pattern, trust the MCP result and update the approach accordingly.

## TypeScript Best Practices

- Use strict type checking.
- Prefer type inference when the type is obvious.
- Avoid the `any` type; use `unknown` when the type is uncertain.

## Angular Best Practices

- Always use standalone components over `NgModules`.
- Do **NOT** set `standalone: true` inside the `@Component`, `@Directive`, and `@Pipe` decorators — it is the default in Angular v20+.
- Use signals for state management.
- Implement lazy loading for feature routes.
- Do **NOT** use the `@HostBinding` and `@HostListener` decorators. Put host bindings inside the `host` object of the `@Component` or `@Directive` decorator instead.
- Use `NgOptimizedImage` for all static images.
  - `NgOptimizedImage` does **not** work for inline base64 images.

## Accessibility Requirements

- MUST pass all AXE checks.
- MUST follow all WCAG AA minimums, including focus management, color contrast, and ARIA attributes.

## Components

- Keep components small and focused on a single responsibility.
- Use `input()` signal instead of the `@Input()` decorator. See https://angular.dev/guide/components/inputs.
- Use `output()` function instead of the `@Output()` decorator. See https://angular.dev/guide/components/outputs.
- Use `computed()` for derived state. See https://angular.dev/guide/signals.
- Set `changeDetection: ChangeDetectionStrategy.OnPush` in the `@Component` decorator.
- Prefer inline templates for small components.
- Prefer Reactive forms instead of Template-driven ones.
- Do **NOT** use `ngClass`; use `class` bindings instead. See https://angular.dev/guide/templates/binding#css-class-and-style-property-bindings.
- Do **NOT** use `ngStyle`; use `style` bindings instead. See https://angular.dev/guide/templates/binding#css-class-and-style-property-bindings.
- When using external templates/styles, use paths relative to the component TS file.

## State Management

- Use signals for local component state.
- Use `computed()` for derived state.
- Keep state transformations pure and predictable.
- Do **NOT** use `mutate` on signals; use `update` or `set` instead.

## Templates

- Keep templates simple and avoid complex logic.
- Use native control flow (`@if`, `@for`, `@switch`) instead of `*ngIf`, `*ngFor`, `*ngSwitch`.
- Use the `async` pipe to handle observables.
- Do not assume globals like `new Date()` are available.
- Use built-in pipes and import pipes when used in a template. See https://angular.dev/guide/templates/pipes.

## Services

- Design services around a single responsibility.
- Use the `providedIn: 'root'` option for singleton services.
- Use the `inject()` function instead of constructor injection.
